{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1 (verses Āṅg_1.219–223)**\n\n> A *veśyā* (prostitute/courtesan), though fit only for pleasure, is superior to her.[^1] If one eats in the same row with her during these rites, or eats together with her, it is a wicked act that causes loss of caste.[^2] For the purification of that sin, one should, according to rule, be covered in a pit in the earth, having dug it for a period of one watch (three hours) or two *ghaṭikās* (forty-eight minutes).[^3] After being lifted out of it, one should then perform the birth rites (*jātakarma*) and others anew. One should also perform a thousand Taptakṛcchra penances according to rule.[^4] With a controlled self, subsisting on barley, he should perform the Cāpāgrayāna rite; then he becomes pure. He should perform five thousand baths, either himself or through a Brahmin.[^5] Then he becomes pure for himself alone. He is not fit for others. Thus spoke Bhṛgu in ancient times.[^6]\n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-86fa77).\n\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-f9ae9b).\n\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-41d863).\n\n[^4]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-f32936).\n\n[^5]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-35e271).\n\n[^6]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-aaa649).",
